/* Method

## In the evening.

1. Grind the seeds. We want the seeds to be part of the dough
instead of just floating around in it. Use a pestle and mortar to
break the seeds down a little bit. They do not need to be very fine.
A food processor can be used but be careful not to pulverize them
too much. The finer the seeds the dried the dough.

1a. In a large bowl, combine the ground seeds and an equal weight of
water and the salt. 

1b. Grind the rye flour.

1c. Keep the soaker and the flour at 80F overnight.

1d. Build the starter using some of the ground rye. Keep it at RT.

## Next morning

2. In a large bowl combine the water, yeast, starter and the soaker.
Mix well. Add the flour and mix to a dough. Smooth out the surface
of the dough.

3. Roll the dough in the sunflower seeds taking care not to fold the
dough. Cover the whole surface.

4. Place the dough in a non-stick paper lined baking tin. *Desired
dough temperature 23C – 24C (73F – 75F). If your dough is warmer,
then it will ferment more rapidly. If it is cooler, then it will
take longer.

5. Cover and ferment at 80F until there are clearly visible cracks
on the surface of the loaf.

6. Spray the dough with water and bake in a pre-heated oven at 180C
(356F) fan off for:

  60 minutes for the 2 pound pan.
  45 minutes for the 1 pound pan.

7. Remove the loaf from the tin and place it back into the oven for:

  30 more minutes for the 2 pound pan.
  20 more minutes for the 1 pound pan.

The internal temperature should read above 94C (200F).

8. Wrap the loaf in a clean cloth to help it retain more moisture
and leave it to cool down completely. I like to rest a bread like
this for 12 hours.

*/

